SIMPLE: signify
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Signify
<hw>Sig"ni*fy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Signified</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Signifying</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F.
<ets>signifier</ets>, L. <ets>significare</ets>; <ets>signum</ets> a
sign + <ets>-ficare</ets> (in comp.) to make. See <er>Sign</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>, and <er>-fy</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To show by a
sign; to communicate by any conventional token, as words, gestures,
signals, or the like; to announce; to make known; to declare; to
express; <as>as, a <ex>signified</ex> his desire to be
present</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I 'll to the king; and <qex>signify</qex> to him⟦br⟧
That thus I have resign'd my charge to you.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The government should <qex>signify</qex> to the Protestants of
Ireland that want of silver is not to be remedied.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To mean; to import; to denote; to betoken.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He bade her tell him what it <qex>signified</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A tale⟦br⟧
Told by an idiot, full of sound and fury,⟦br⟧
<qex>Signifying</qex> nothing.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Signify</xex> is often used impersonally; as, it
<xex>signifies</xex> nothing, it does not <xex>signify</xex>, that is,
it is of no importance.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To express; manifest; declare; utter; intimate;
betoken; denote; imply; mean.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>signing</ent>⟦br⟧
